    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that bucket thing makes sense but it's still frustrating. can u explain the actual math behind it? like how is the interest calculated every month so i can see exactly where my money is going vs what's actually hitting the principal",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure, I can explain that. Your student loan interest is typically calculated using the daily balance method. In this method, the interest for the month is determined by multiplying the average daily balance of your loan by the monthly interest rate. The formula looks like this:\n\nInterest = Average Daily Balance * Monthly Interest Rate\n\nAs for how your monthly payment is split between interest and principal, this is determined by your loan's amortization schedule. The schedule shows how much of each monthly payment goes toward interest and how much goes toward the principal. At the beginning of your loan term, a larger portion of your payment will go toward interest, and a smaller portion will go toward the principal. As the principal balance decreases, a larger portion of your payment will go toward reducing the principal, and a smaller portion will go toward interest.\n\nI hope this helps you understand how the interest and principal are calculated and how the amortization schedule works. If you have any more questions, feel free to ask!",
